SOC126 - Suspicious New Autorun Value Detected | EventID: 61 | Severity: High | Status: CLOSED

---

Summary
---------
On Feb 14, 2021, at 06:40 PM UTC, the MSOC Security team received an alert titled “SOC126 – Suspicious New Autorun Value Detected.” The alert was generated on host  "KatharinePRD (IP: 172.16.15.78)".

The alert identified the execution of a file named "OliwciaPrivInstaller.exe", which was configured to run automatically on system boot, indicating a persistence mechanism. OSINT analysis confirmed the file hash as malicious.

Further investigation revealed a suspicious process named "creditcard" located at `/home/katharine/Documents/creditcard`. The process was executed with "root privileges", which is highly abnormal for a user directory binary and indicative of potential malicious activity.

Timeline analysis showed that the process had been present since "September 22, 2020", suggesting a "long-term compromise" prior to detection.

Although the endpoint reported the malware as cleaned, the presence of persistence mechanisms and a root-level process indicates that the system was fully compromised, requiring deeper investigation and remediation.

